<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910620-0175</DOCNO><DOCID>910620-0175.</DOCID><HL>   PBS's Flagship TV Station   To Dismiss 14% of Its Staff</HL><DATE>06/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Beset by financial problems including a cut instate aid and a decline in viewer donations, WNET, theflagship television station of the Public BroadcastingService, said it would fire 14% of its 500-member staff.   As part of the drastic cutbacks, WNET also said it wouldeliminate programming on Saturdays and Sundays from midnightto 6 a.m. Also, the entire management team will berestructured, as six senior vice president positions areamong 69 jobs that will be cut.</LP><TEXT>   The station, with an annual operating budget of $100million, recently had its funding from New York state reducedby $5 million. Viewer membership also slipped slightly,William F. Baker, WNET president, said in an interview. &quot;Wedid the budget, and the difference of what we needed withwhat we had is $10 million,&quot; he said. &quot;This is serious stuff.I'm counting erasers and pencils.&quot;   The cutbacks will mean a &quot;consolidation&quot; of locallyproduced public affairs broadcasts, said Mr. Baker, referringto the two half-hour nightly shows produced at the station,&quot;Thirteen Live&quot; and &quot;Live Wire.&quot; He declined to be morespecific.   Financial woes plague other PBS stations as well. Lastmonth, WGBH in Boston canceled its 15-year-old award-winning10 p.m. local newscast. And last week, KCET in Los Angeleseliminated about 40 positions and cut $2.4 million forlocally produced programs.</TEXT></DOC>